cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.CYBER, cs.IR, cs.MM

This paper focuses on the polarization of users around news outlets on Facebook in different European countries, which involves social media analysis and modeling user behavior. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also discusses the impact of misinformation and selective exposure, which relates to cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences). Additionally, the paper mentions the role of trust in information broadcaster, which could fall under cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity) or cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper includes analysis of posting behavior and user interaction patterns, which could be relevant to cs.MM (Multimedia).
